When I first started my podcast, I was feeling anxious about starting something new or who would even listen.

I wanted to wait until everything was as I envisioned, so I…

I studied EVERYTHING I could about the equipment needed.

I listened to many podcasts to see what I would/wouldn’t do differently.

I overthought who would say yes/no to being a guest on the show.

But you know what?

All of these things were just distractions from me fulfilling my purpose:

Helping women HEAL!

I’m so happy that I stopped wasting time and just DID it.

In 2017 I dated an up-and-coming model.

I helped him build his brand by leveraging my knowledge, contacts and network and eventually getting signed by agencies in Canada and Africa.

Only to find out he cheated on me with a past girlfriend and I was the last to know…(after making it “Instagram official”)

Unable to cancel our trip to Paris that was scheduled in the upcoming weeks, I decided last minute to go solo and stay on the opposite side of the city from him. 

This trip to Paris was supposed to be romantic but I spent the majority of it alone and in tears.

At the time, I didn’t know how I was going to get through the heartache and shame I felt.

Experiencing 6 months of grieving and in a deep depression.

6 years later…I can joke about this experience because I took the time to heal.

In a deep dive to holistically heal mind, body and soul, is where I discovered peace, clarity and connection.

It is impossible to be truly wise without some real-life hardship. 

Finding a community and safe spaces off and online helped me get through. 

Social connection builds resilience, and resilience helps create post-traumatic wisdom, and that wisdom leads to hope. 

It takes time and effort to heal, but it is possible with the right support and resources.

Single or in a relationship, if we do not know how to love ourselves first it can affect all the other relationships around us.

Here are 5 tips on how to love yourself first

1. Take time for yourself - Take some time to reflect and relax. This could be through exercise, reading, walking, meditating, or whatever helps you to relax and refocus.

2. Set boundaries - It's important to honour your own needs first and set boundaries with others to ensure that you are respected.

3. Be kind to yourself - Practice positive self-talk and not be too hard on yourself. Celebrate your successes and accept mistakes as learning opportunities.

4. Do something that makes you happy - Find activities that make you feel good and prioritize them in your life.

5. Take care of your body - Eating healthy and exercising can help you feel better physically and mentally. It can also help to boost your self-esteem.

How are you celebrating your love today?

We are programmed to think negatively…📉

There are many reasons why humans may be programmed to think negatively, including:

1. Evolutionary survival instincts: Our brains are wired to prioritize potential threats to ensure our survival. 

We may naturally focus more on negative experiences and potential dangers.

2. Cultural and societal influences: Negative thinking can also be reinforced by cultural and societal norms, which may emphasize the importance of being prepared for the worst-case scenario or the value of being self-critical.

3. Personal experiences: Our past experiences can shape our current thought patterns, particularly if we have experienced negative events or trauma. 

This can lead to a tendency to anticipate negative outcomes and dwell on negative thoughts.

We have to actually train ourselves to focus on the good. 

So the next time you feel a negative thought, see how much effort it takes to focus on something positive. 📈

We typically listen at one of four levels:

1. Ignoring the other person
2. Pretending to listen
3. Selective listening
4. Attentive listening

Listening with L.U.V. is part of attentive listening. 

Use your eyes, ears, and heart to listen.

👂🏾L: Listen to what is being said but pay attention to the body language and tone without interrupting. 

👂🏾U: Understand what is being said from their perspective without taking offence. 

👂🏾V: Validate what was just shared with you as it may have been challenging for them to express their feelings.

A great way to start practicing validation is to use some of these verbal techniques:

💜Reflection. Show you’re listening by repeating what you heard the other person say. Use descriptive language, such as “I hear you. You’re upset because it seems I wasn’t mindful of the time” rather than judgmental language.

💜Seek clarification. Ask questions to make sure you’re hearing what the other person intended. For example, “So you feel that my showing up late is disrespectful of your time, right?” This can also help you both get better at expressing your thoughts and emotions clearly.

💜Normalize. Communicate that what the other person is feeling makes sense based on their experience or perspective—and that others in their situation might feel similarly. For example, “I can empathize that you feel neglected because I showed up late. I can see how being left alone for longer than you expected might make you feel abandoned.”

Start listening with L.U.V.

I promise it will change your conversations and relationships.

5 ways of how to set healthy boundaries

1. Identify your limits: Take some time to reflect on your needs, values, and priorities, and identify what you’re comfortable with and what you’re not. 
2. Communicate clearly: When setting boundaries, it’s important to communicate your needs and expectations clearly and assertively without being aggressive or passive. Use “I” statements and specify what you’re comfortable with. 
3. Be consistent: Once you’ve set your boundaries, it’s important to enforce them consistently. This helps you establish a pattern of behaviour that others can understand and respect. 
4. Practice self-care: Setting and enforcing boundaries can be challenging, so taking care of yourself in the process is important. Make time for self-care activities that help you recharge and stay centred. 
5. Respect others’ boundaries: Just as you have the right to set your own boundaries, others have the right to set theirs. Respect others’ boundaries and communicate your needs and expectations in a respectful and considerate way.

It’s a common misconception that strong people don’t need help or support. 

In reality, everyone can benefit from checking in on their mental well-being, regardless of how “strong” they appear. 

Here are three reasons why it’s important to check on your strong friends:

❤️‍🩹They may be suffering in silence: 

Just because someone appears to have everything together on the outside doesn’t mean they aren’t struggling on the inside. Strong friends may feel like they have to maintain a certain image or reputation and may be hesitant to share their struggles with others. By checking in on them, you can create a safe space for them to open up and get the support they need.

❤️‍🩹They may be taking on too much: 

Strong friends often take on many responsibilities and try to handle everything themselves. While this can be admirable, it can also lead to burnout and stress. By checking in on them, you can help them identify areas where they may need to delegate or ask for help.

❤️‍🩹They may be experiencing mental health issues: 

Mental health issues can affect anyone, regardless of how strong or capable they may appear. People who appear strong on the outside may be more prone to anxiety or depression due to the pressure they put on themselves to maintain that image. By checking in on your strong friends, you can help them recognize any symptoms they may be experiencing and encourage them to seek professional help if needed.

Remember, checking in on someone doesn’t have to be a big gesture. 

A simple text, phone call, or coffee date can show your strong friends that you care about them and are there to support them.

Dealing with people with unrealistic expectations of you can be a challenging experience. 

It’s important to remember that you can only do what is within your abilities and capabilities and that it’s okay to say no or set boundaries when necessary. 

Here are some tips on how to respond to people that have unrealistic expectations of you:

⚠️Be honest: Communicate openly and honestly with the person, explaining why their expectations are unrealistic and what you can realistically deliver. Be clear about your limitations and boundaries.

⚠️Offer alternatives: If you can’t meet their expectations, try to offer an alternative solution or compromise you can agree on.

⚠️Stand your ground: Don’t be afraid to say no or assert your boundaries. Remember that it’s okay to prioritize your own needs and well-being.

⚠️Don’t take it personally: Sometimes, people’s unrealistic expectations reflect their own issues and insecurities. Do not take it personally, and remember that it’s not your responsibility to fulfill their every demand.

⚠️Seek support: If you’re struggling to deal with someone’s unrealistic expectations, seek support from friends, family, or a professional counsellor. A support system can help you maintain your perspective and cope with difficult situations.

Being in nature is a transformative experience that can awaken our senses and make us feel more alive. 

When we spend time in natural environments, whether a forest, a beach, or a park, we are surrounded by a diverse range of sights, sounds, smells, and textures that we may not encounter in our daily lives.

One of the ways that being in nature liberates our senses is by allowing us to disconnect from the distractions of modern life. 

When surrounded by technology, noise, and artificial lighting, our senses can become overwhelmed and desensitized. 

However, when we’re in a natural environment, our senses are free to take in the beauty and complexity of the natural world. 

We can hear the rustling of leaves, feel the sun’s warmth on our skin, and smell the scent of wildflowers. 

This sensory input can help us to feel more alive and present in the moment.

Additionally, spending time in nature has a range of physical and mental health benefits. 

Studies have found that being in natural environments can reduce stress, improve mood, and boost cognitive function. 

When our senses are engaged, our brains release neurotransmitters like dopamine and serotonin, which can improve our mood and enhance our cognitive abilities.

Taking breaks is essential for maintaining good physical and mental health.

Here are three reasons why it’s essential to take breaks:

Studies have shown that people who take breaks throughout the day are more productive than those who work non-stop. Breaks give your brain a chance to rest and recharge, which can help you focus better and work more efficiently when you return to your tasks.

2. Improved physical health: Sitting for long periods can be harmful to your health. Taking breaks to stand up, stretch, and move around can help reduce the risk of health problems such as back pain, obesity, and heart disease. Taking a break to go for a walk or do some light exercise can also help improve your energy levels and mood.

3. Reduced stress: Working non-stop for long periods can be highly stressful. Taking breaks can help you reduce stress and anxiety by giving you time to relax and recharge. Taking a few deep breaths, meditating, or doing some other form of relaxation during your break can help you feel more calm and more centred, which can help you better handle the demands of your workday.

Overall, taking breaks is essential for maintaining good physical and mental health, boosting productivity, and reducing stress. 

So, be sure to take regular breaks to help you stay healthy, happy, and productive.

Making the most of what you have is a valuable skill that can help you live a fulfilling life. 

It means using your resources in the best possible way to achieve your goals while being grateful for what you already have. 

Here are some tips to help you make the most of what you have:

💜Be grateful: 
Take time each day to appreciate the things you have in your life. This can include your health, family, friends, job, home, and more. 

Focusing on what you have instead of what you lack can help you feel happier and more content.

💜Prioritize: 
Identify the most important things to you and focus your time and energy on them. 

This can help you avoid wasting time on things that don’t matter and instead invest your resources in the areas that will help you achieve your goals.

💜Be creative: 
Use your imagination to find new ways to use what you have. 

For example, if you have limited resources, you can still create something beautiful or valuable by repurposing items or finding alternative solutions.

💜Learn new skills: 
Investing in your own education and personal development can help you make the most of what you have. 

By learning new skills, you can become more self-sufficient and resourceful and find new ways to achieve your goals.

By following these tips, you can make the most of what you have and live a fulfilling life. 

Remember to be patient, stay positive, and strive for your goals.

Today’s affirmation:

ALL GOOD THINGS COME TO ME, FLOW TO ME 🙏🏾

Positive self-talk has helped me go from not believing something is possible to living the vision. 

When I released my second book in 2016, “A Walk In My Stilettos: 111 Affirmations To Help You Heal”, it was owed to how prayer and affirmation saved me from self-destruction. 

Affirmations (a statement said confidently about a perceived truth) have helped thousands of people make significant life changes. 

But they don’t always work for everyone.

You must believe in the words you are saying. 

Feel the power behind them and let them marinate in your subconscious. 

We repeatedly tell ourselves things every day and don’t even realize them. 

What lies are you currently telling yourself about YOU? 

These unwholesome statements can stay with us in the conscious or unconscious mind, which we then reinforce throughout our lives.
To “affirm” something, by dictionary definition, means that you are declaring it to be true. 

So when you affirm that you are fit when you are not, wealthy when you are financially struggling or loved when you are lonely, you are holding a vision for what you know CAN be true.

So affirm this with me:

ALL GOOD THINGS COME TO ME, FLOW TO ME 🙏🏾
